  • Then, we should resample our time series.
In [14]:
# Convert tpep_pickup_datetime to datetime object

df['tpep_pickup_datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(df['tpep_pickup_datetime'])

# Take the rows that contain user input date
new = df[df['tpep_pickup_datetime'].dt.date == input_date]

# Resample the data with user input resolution
new = new.resample(str(input_resolution)+'min', on='tpep_pickup_datetime')['tpep_pickup_datetime'].size()

# Plot the resampled data
new.plot(title = "Day: " + str(input_date), xlabel = "Time", ylabel="Number of trips")

df_joined_zones = pd.read_sql_query("SELECT  t.id,  t.tpep_pickup_datetime,  t.tpep_dropoff_datetime,  z.location_i AS pickup_location_id,  z2.location_i AS dropoff_location_id FROM  yellow_geom t  JOIN taxi_zones z ON ST_Contains(z.geom, t.l_pickup)  JOIN taxi_zones z2 ON ST_Contains(z2.geom, t.l_dropoff)", conn)

# Convert the pickup and dropoff columns to datetime objects

df_joined_zones["tpep_pickup_datetime"] = pd.to_datetime(df_joined_zones["tpep_pickup_datetime"])
df_joined_zones["tpep_dropoff_datetime"] = pd.to_datetime(df_joined_zones["tpep_dropoff_datetime"])


# Create a datetime range with the user input interval

start_time = pd.to_datetime(input_doi)
end_time = start_time + pd.Timedelta(days=1)
time_range = pd.date_range(start_time, end_time, freq=input_interval)


results_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["start_time", "end_time", "pickup_location_id", "dropoff_location_id", "count"])

for i in range(len(time_range)-1):
    
    start_time = time_range[i]
    end_time = time_range[i+1]

    # Take rows that fall into our calculated time interval
    
    interval_df = df_joined_zones[(df_joined_zones["tpep_pickup_datetime"] >= start_time) & (df_joined_zones["tpep_pickup_datetime"] < end_time)]

    # Group by pickup and dropoff locations and count the number of trips
    
    count_df = interval_df.groupby(["pickup_location_id", "dropoff_location_id"]).size().reset_index(name="count")
    
    # Take the input k counts and append them to resulting dataframe
    
    top_counts = count_df.nlargest(int(input_k), "count")
    for i, row in top_counts.iterrows():
        results_df = results_df.append({"start_time": start_time, "end_time": end_time, "pickup_location_id": row["pickup_location_id"], "dropoff_location_id": row["dropoff_location_id"], "count": row["count"]}, ignore_index=True)

Part 4¶

Project description:¶

ChatGPT is the most popular tool in the software world for several months. It is a large language model developed by OpenAI, based on the GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) architecture. It is capable of generating human-like text in response to a given prompt, allowing it to engage in conversation with users. ChatGPT was trained on a massive amount of text data, allowing it to learn patterns and relationships in language and generate coherent and contextually appropriate responses.

OpenAI offers its API to developers. With the OpenAI API, developers can integrate the latest natural language processing (NLP), machine learning, and deep learning algorithms into their applications, making them smarter and more sophisticated.

This project will take user prompts about NYC Taxis and generate useful outputs (i.e. trip duration estimastion, trip price calculation, route recommendation etc.) based on prompts using OpenAI API and NYC Taxi Dataset. Also the project might visualize its outputs and integrate with QGIS.

Project Purpose & Goals:¶

Project Purpose:

The purpose of this project is to leverage the NYC Taxi dataset to create a tool that can provide useful information to taxi riders and users in New York City. By using machine learning models and natural language processing, the project aims to generate accurate and contextually appropriate responses to user prompts about taxi trips. Additionally, by visualizing this information on a map using QGIS, the project seeks to provide a more engaging and intuitive user experience.

Project Goals:

  • To develop a tool that uses the OpenAI API to generate text-based outputs in response to user prompts about NYC taxi trips.
  • To create machine learning models based on the NYC Taxi dataset that can estimate trip costs, predict taxi demand, and recommend alternate pickup locations or routes.
  • To integrate these models with the OpenAI API to provide accurate and contextually appropriate responses to user prompts.
  • To visualize the generated outputs on a QGIS map, allowing users to easily understand and interact with the information.

Project Features:¶

This feature list might grow or shrink depending on project deadline and OpenAI API limits.

  • Generate descriptions of taxi routes: Generate descriptions of taxi routes based on the pickup and dropoff locations in the NYC Taxi Dataset using OpenAI API. For example, the generated text could describe landmarks, historical sites, or notable buildings along the route.

  • Estimate trip costs: Use the OpenAI API to generate estimates of taxi trip costs based on pickup and dropoff locations in the NYC taxi dataset. These estimates could be displayed on a QGIS map.

  • Predict taxi demand: Use the NYC Taxi Dataset to train a machine learning model to predict taxi demand in different parts of the city. You could then use the OpenAI API to generate recommendations for passengers based on the predicted demand, such as suggesting alternate pickup locations or routes to avoid traffic.

Project Roadmap:¶

  1. Data Preparation

    • Clean the NYC Taxi dataset by removing any duplicates, missing values, or inconsistent data.
    • Preprocess the dataset by converting it to a format that can be used with the OpenAI API.

  2. Register for the OpenAI API and obtain an API key.

    • Integrate the OpenAI API into the project by installing the OpenAI Python library and setting up the API credentials.
    • Create a Python script to interact with the OpenAI API, allowing it to generate text-based outputs based on user prompts.
    • Note: OpenAI gives only 3 months free usage.

  3. Feature Development

    • Develop features to estimate trip costs, predict taxi demand, and recommend alternate pickup locations or routes.
    • Train machine learning models using the NYC Taxi dataset to predict trip costs, taxi demand, and other relevant metrics.
    • Use the OpenAI API to generate text-based outputs based on these models, allowing the user to make informed decisions about their taxi trips.
